idence -- t17 The construction of the enemy in pre-Viking England -- t18 Warriors and warlike kings in the Gesta Karoli of Notker the Stammerer -- t19 Early medieval ‘warrior’ images and the concept of Gefolgschaft -- t20 Conclusion – militarisation -- tSelect bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe societies of ancient Europe underwent a continual process of militarisation, and this would come to be a defining characteristic of the early Middle Ages. The process was neither linear nor mono-causal, but it affected society as a whole, encompassing features like the lack of demarcation between the military and civil spheres of the population, the significance attributed to weapons beyond their military function and the wide recognition of martial values. Early medieval militarisation assembles twenty studies that use both written and archaeological evidence to explore the phenomenon of militarisation and its impact on the development of the societies of early medieval Europe. The interdisciplinary investigations break new ground and will be essential reading for scholars and students of related fields, as well as non-specialists with an interest in early medieval history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aMilitarizationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMilitarizationzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMilitary archaeology. 0aMilitary history, Medieval. 7aHISTORY / Military / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon.  aByzantium.  aFranks.  aGoths.  aLombards.  aVisigoths.  aarchaeology.  aelite.  amilitary.  aweapons.1 aBennett, Ellora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Ellora, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerndt, Guid